WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.580 --> 00:00:09.230
&gt;&gt;Bill Wile: Hi. Good afternoon. Thanks for
everybody coming today, both here and I guess

00:00:09.230 --> 00:00:14.139
we've got some, some video links as well.

00:00:14.139 --> 00:00:28.929
I'm Bill Wile and it's with great pleasure
that I welcome you to Green@ Google which

00:00:28.929 --> 00:00:41.820
is our speaker series that welcomes authors
to Google to talk about various environmental

00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:44.720
and sustainability topics.

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:57.150
First I'd like to introduce our speaker who
is one of the most remarkable environmental

00:00:57.150 --> 00:01:09.550
advocates living today. He's inspired at least
one if not two or three generations of, of

00:01:09.550 --> 00:01:15.060
people over the last many years, including
myself.

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:30.060
As I was writing this I was, I was kind of
struck by the number of parallels between

00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:43.780
our speaker's pioneering work and biography
and our own Google history. I should say that

00:01:43.780 --> 00:01:52.920
I could probably spend the entire hour summarizing
his biography -

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:53.920
[laughter]

00:01:53.920 --> 00:02:01.159
you guys don't want me to do that.

00:02:01.159 --> 00:02:02.159
[laughter]

00:02:02.159 --> 00:02:15.790
So, first of all he's a Stanford graduate
the place where Larry met Sergey. Thirty nine

00:02:15.790 --> 00:02:32.080
years before Google Earth was launched he
initiated a campaign which resulted in NASA

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:48.090
releasing the first color images of earth
from space. These pictures also helped to

00:02:48.090 --> 00:02:55.410
inspire the creation of the first Earth Day
celebration.

00:02:55.410 --> 00:03:13.230
He is best known as the founder of the original
Whole Earth Catalog. Some of you are probably

00:03:13.230 --> 00:03:27.660
too young to know what that is, some of us
aren't.

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:31.819
&gt;&gt;voice in audience: Fossil.

00:03:31.819 --> 00:03:40.150
&gt;&gt;Bill Wile: Thank you. Yes, fossil. I'm guilty.

00:03:40.150 --> 00:03:41.200
[laughter]

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:54.920
It was likened to and I quote "Google in paperback
form." I don't think that was said in the

00:03:54.920 --> 00:04:10.180
'60's but more recently. And he received a
national book award for it.

00:04:10.180 --> 00:04:21.409
He was the original organizer of the Hacker
Conference popularizing the famous phrase

00:04:21.409 --> 00:04:34.379
"information wants to be free" an idea which
continues to become even more popular today

00:04:34.379 --> 00:04:46.479
and certainly resonates with our mission to
make the world's information easily and universally

00:04:46.479 --> 00:04:49.939
accessible and, and useful.

00:04:49.939 --> 00:05:03.280
He also co-founded The Well, another thing
that many of you are probably too young to

00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:05.120
know about -

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:16.669
with Larry Brilliant who was an executive
director of Google.org for several years.

00:05:16.669 --> 00:05:23.710
It was one of the first and longest lasting
online communities and, and really paved the

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:33.509
way in many ways for every online business
from Amazon to eBay to Google and, and so

00:05:33.509 --> 00:05:34.509
on.

00:05:34.509 --> 00:05:49.499
Stewart is a self proclaimed environmental
heretic; so he's not afraid to challenge the

00:05:49.499 --> 00:05:51.759
status quo.

00:05:51.759 --> 00:06:07.560
He's here today to talk about his latest book
"Whole Earth Discipline: An Ecopragmatist

00:06:07.560 --> 00:06:25.729
Manifesto." A book which has been hailed as
one of the most important books of

00:06:25.729 --> 00:06:50.090
the decade as well as ominous and exhilarating
and mind bending.

00:06:50.090 --> 00:07:09.420
I hope you'll find his ideas engaging and
provocative as well.

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:16.819
Please join me in welcoming Stewart Brand.

00:07:16.819 --> 00:07:17.879
[applause]

00:07:17.879 --> 00:07:35.800
&gt;&gt;Stewart Brand: Alright. How's our sound
are we okay all the way in back and stuff

00:07:35.800 --> 00:07:45.099
like that? Okay. Great. Good to go.

00:07:45.099 --> 00:08:02.199
&gt;&gt;Bill Wile: One, one other point of order.

00:08:02.199 --> 00:08:03.449
[laughter]

00:08:03.449 --> 00:08:15.529
Sorry. So this is being recorded and will
be put on YouTube so when you ask questions

00:08:15.529 --> 00:08:23.169
please remember that; that this is public;
this is not a private Google talk and there

00:08:23.169 --> 00:08:25.000
is on microphones.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:38.310
&gt;&gt;Stewart Brand: I wonder what things you
don't say in those circumstances, but I won't

00:08:38.310 --> 00:08:39.310
ask.

00:08:39.310 --> 00:08:40.310
[laughter]

00:08:40.310 --> 00:08:44.290
&gt;&gt;Bill Wile: We can't tell you.

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:45.290
[laughter]

00:08:45.290 --> 00:08:58.530
&gt;&gt;Stewart Brand: Yeah, quick revisit. At age
of 10 I gave my pledge as an American to save

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:08.530
and faithfully to defend from waste the natural
resources my country - its air, soil, and

00:09:08.530 --> 00:09:21.610
minerals, its forests, waters and wildlife.
That came from not some kind of lefty thing,

00:09:21.610 --> 00:09:25.010
but outdoor life.

00:09:25.010 --> 00:09:40.900
The conservation pledge was promoted by conservatives,
basically hunters and fisherman and its relative

00:09:40.900 --> 00:10:03.160
to remember the environmental movement was
basically begun in this country by duck hunters.

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:18.150
And it has been a, a conservative thing from
the start and it's only lately got identified,

00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:27.450
I think over identified with being on the
left.

00:10:27.450 --> 00:10:50.510
So I went to Stanford, got a degree in ecology,
did The Whole Earth Catalog '68, in the '70's

00:10:50.510 --> 00:11:01.930
I worked for the first Jerry Brown administration.

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:03.030
[laughter]

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:16.610
And he, that administration set in motion
the regulations and rules and norms so that

00:11:16.610 --> 00:11:29.700
Californians emit half the greenhouse gases
of the residents of any other state per capita.

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:38.830
That lasted through several Republican governors
and it's an impressive accomplishment.

00:11:38.830 --> 00:11:52.870
So a current event for me is this book called
Whole Earth Discipline. I'll just mention

00:11:52.870 --> 00:12:14.820
a couple of things that
are in it, but I won't touch on much today.

00:12:14.820 --> 00:12:26.950
I'm trying to move on thinking from the idea
of natural capital as a way to think about

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:36.000
ecosystems services and just to say, "Look,
it's infrastructure." Yeah, it's natural infrastructure,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:47.400
but a bridge is an infrastructure and so is
the river under it.

00:12:47.400 --> 00:13:25.270
Precautionary principle is fine if and only
if it allows things to go forward and be tried.

00:13:25.270 --> 00:13:36.480
So I want the precautionary principle matched
with a vigilance principle where you keep

00:13:36.480 --> 00:13:48.540
an eye on stuff. You try it and then out of
precaution you watch if it's gonna do good

00:13:48.540 --> 00:13:51.080
things or bad things.

00:13:51.080 --> 00:13:57.390
It's particularly nice to be talking here
at Google because the rethinking green I'm

00:13:57.390 --> 00:14:07.340
doing basically is trying to get the whole
environmental movement and everybody who listens

00:14:07.340 --> 00:14:21.650
to them to think like scientists and even
more to think like engineers. That it's not

00:14:21.650 --> 00:14:28.720
always saying no to things but often saying
yes, but let's do it this particularly cool

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:29.720
way.

00:14:29.720 --> 00:14:47.710
That involves thinking like a fox instead
of a hedgehog. Being able to hold a whole

00:14:47.710 --> 00:15:04.810
many things, many ideas, some of them contradictory
in your mind at the same time, instead of

00:15:04.810 --> 00:15:14.310
pledging your entire life and allegiance to
one hedgehogeque ideology.

00:15:14.310 --> 00:15:23.000
So I'm trying to move people from romance
to science to engineering and we're realizing

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:35.150
that we are now the keystone species on the
planet and it is basically ours to guard either

00:15:35.150 --> 00:15:42.710
well or badly but we don't have a choice not
to.

00:15:42.710 --> 00:15:44.470
[pause]

00:15:44.470 --> 00:15:55.120
The news items in the book and ones that are
maybe more directly relevant here and these

00:15:55.120 --> 00:16:03.240
were more fun to illustrate is cities are
green, nuclear power is green, genetic engineering

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:08.650
is green and I fear that geoengineering may
well be necessary.

00:16:08.650 --> 00:16:12.990
Let's quickly visit the climate aspects of
that.

00:16:12.990 --> 00:16:23.820
I won't go through the whole trip that I'm
sure Al Gore did on climate, but the point

00:16:23.820 --> 00:16:35.680
that interests me most about it is the degree
to which it is a severe non-linear system

00:16:35.680 --> 00:16:43.060
with various hidden positive feedbacks, tipping
points, thresholds and whatnot. This is just

00:16:43.060 --> 00:16:50.350
one diagram that climatologists use to remind
themselves of the things that we don't know

00:16:50.350 --> 00:16:59.790
yet. So there's a hell of a lot more science
that needs to come along on all these subjects.

00:16:59.790 --> 00:17:06.250
What happens when climate really affects things
is with warming you get drought; with drought

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:14.529
you get a fight over lowering carrying capacity
for, for humans, over resources, over water

00:17:14.529 --> 00:17:35.009
in the case of Darfur. If things go badly
with climate Darfur may be seen as the first

00:17:35.009 --> 00:17:36.419
of the climate wars.

00:17:36.419 --> 00:17:43.669
A good book on this sort of subject is called
Constant Battles by Steven LeBlanc.

00:17:43.669 --> 00:17:51.059
Another potential conflict area is the glaciers
of the Himalaya, no they're probably not gonna

00:17:51.059 --> 00:18:01.460
all melt by 2035 as we heard from the IPCC,
but they are nevertheless melting and the

00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:12.619
entire Himalayan plateau feeds rivers that
provide water in the dry season to 40% of

00:18:12.619 --> 00:18:20.649
humanity. Mostly those rivers flow through
several different nations, several of which

00:18:20.649 --> 00:18:28.370
are nuclear armed. If they get to fighting
over resources it could get pretty ugly.

00:18:28.370 --> 00:18:37.730
A couple of good climate books - this is interesting,
this is such a green presentation that all

00:18:37.730 --> 00:18:41.399
my colors have gone green.

00:18:41.399 --> 00:18:42.399
[laughter]

00:18:42.399 --> 00:18:54.320
There really are other colors in the original.
This is kind of fun, but it's a little sickly

00:18:54.320 --> 00:18:57.809
I'd have to say.

00:18:57.809 --> 00:19:09.110
Anyway a couple books I recommend is James
Lovelock, "The Vanishing Face of Gaia" and

00:19:09.110 --> 00:19:12.710
"Six Degrees" by Mark Lynas.

00:19:12.710 --> 00:19:24.460
With this group of engineers I will raise
a question that is - I don't usually raise

00:19:24.460 --> 00:19:32.610
in public - which is there may be hidden negative
impacts, we hope so, in the climate system.

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:40.440
There may be a flywheel of momentum effect
that slows down some of these tipping points

00:19:40.440 --> 00:19:42.240
and positive feedbacks.

00:19:42.240 --> 00:19:50.460
There is still carbon disappearing from the
atmosphere that we don't know where it's going;

00:19:50.460 --> 00:20:02.750
mysterious carbon sink. It may be going in
the oceans, it may be going in the soil, it

00:20:02.750 --> 00:20:14.100
may be going in the trees growing because
of CO2, but we, we need to figure out what

00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:23.610
that is and either at least work with it or
not into it.

00:20:23.610 --> 00:20:25.980
Lots of science.

00:20:25.980 --> 00:20:37.850
Likewise another possible positive feedback;
a whole lot of the book goes on about microorganisms;

00:20:37.850 --> 00:20:47.059
our best friend 'cause they create the atmosphere
that we live with. There's a microorganism

00:20:47.059 --> 00:21:07.960
in the oceans called Emiliania huxleyi, EHUX
to its friends, that makes blooms that you

00:21:07.960 --> 00:21:43.340
can see from space; they increase the reflectance
of the earth when they do that; they fix carbon

00:21:43.340 --> 00:21:53.620
in their shells; the shells then sink to the
bottom of the ocean and they are a carbon

00:21:53.620 --> 00:22:00.200
fixer and there's some sign with lab work
that they may not add to acidification of

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:01.451
the oceans. Lots more science needed there.

00:22:01.451 --> 00:22:11.510
So moving from climate to the whole perspective
on demographics; the major fact that I'm trying

00:22:11.510 --> 00:22:19.740
to get everybody who's thinking about these
issues, climate and green issues and so on,

00:22:19.740 --> 00:22:35.440
is that five out of six of us do not live
in the developed world, we live in the developing

00:22:35.440 --> 00:22:56.620
world where a whole hell of a lot is going
on. People are moving to cities, they're educating

00:22:56.620 --> 00:23:07.080
their kids, they're getting the hell out of
poverty and it is a demographic change as

00:23:07.080 --> 00:23:23.129
large as any in the history of humanity going
on now. We've now passed the majority of people

00:23:23.129 --> 00:23:33.700
living on the earth are in cities, I call
it city planet and the expectation is that

00:23:33.700 --> 00:23:47.820
by about mid-century we will be up to 80 percent
[inaudible] which is what it is in developed

00:23:47.820 --> 00:23:50.899
countries now.

00:23:50.899 --> 00:23:58.870
The overall numbers are incredible. One point
three million new people a week in cities,

00:23:58.870 --> 00:24:11.690
70 million a year. Some are being born there;
most are moving there. And when they move,

00:24:11.690 --> 00:24:19.419
they move from primarily from subsistence
agriculture situations which are beautiful

00:24:19.419 --> 00:24:30.669
to look at but they're hell to work in. They
are poverty jobs, they're ecological disasters

00:24:30.669 --> 00:24:33.909
built specifically inside of marginal land.

00:24:33.909 --> 00:24:42.429
When people move off this land, especially
in the tropical areas it grows back pretty

00:24:42.429 --> 00:25:01.869
fast; the animals come back because they're
no longer being killed for bush meat and this

00:25:01.869 --> 00:25:16.960
is a, a part of the green advantage of cities.
That's in the developing world.

00:25:16.960 --> 00:25:35.369
In the developed world, as we are increasingly
finding, cities are a great place to live

00:25:35.369 --> 00:25:51.429
if you wanna use less materials; less energy;
and by the way have a more exciting life.

00:25:51.429 --> 00:26:08.450
So people are moving away from the poverty
trap, but they're moving toward action. Now

00:26:08.450 --> 00:26:26.690
they don't get to go to downtown Manhattan
right away, they start with squatter cities;

00:26:26.690 --> 00:26:27.899
slums.

00:26:27.899 --> 00:26:38.279
And there is no end of economic activity going
on there; in the informal economy as it's

00:26:38.279 --> 00:26:48.460
called. I talked about this a couple years
ago, so I won't go in great depth about it,

00:26:48.460 --> 00:26:56.350
but a good book on the subject is Shadow Cities
by Robert Neuwirth.

00:26:56.350 --> 00:27:12.180
An important point to realize is that, that
people are getting out of poverty; part of

00:27:12.180 --> 00:27:23.859
what they're doing is that they're moving
to the bright lights in cities to buy electricity.

00:27:23.859 --> 00:27:33.789
If it's not there, readily available, they
don't have money to pay for it, they steal

00:27:33.789 --> 00:27:39.529
it. Like here in Rio. They do the same with
water and cable TV and by and by if they've

00:27:39.529 --> 00:27:42.960
stole well enough gradually it gentrifies
and these things become legal, but it starts

00:27:42.960 --> 00:27:43.960
out illegal.

00:27:43.960 --> 00:28:00.249
Squatter cities are the densest social capital
activities in the world. Look at an edge like

00:28:00.249 --> 00:28:11.519
this in Sao Paulo and you start to see why
cities derive so much of their power from

00:28:11.519 --> 00:28:26.379
proximity. In this case, you've got people
that live on the left in the boring part of

00:28:26.379 --> 00:28:34.749
town walk to work over in the, in the exciting
part of town over the boring empty swimming

00:28:34.749 --> 00:28:51.100
pools on the right as nannies and gardeners
and guards and cooks and whatnot, and then

00:28:51.100 --> 00:28:58.409
walk home to the interesting life on the left.

00:28:58.409 --> 00:29:06.340
Proximity is everything in cities. It is what
drives people to them, it's what rewards them

00:29:06.340 --> 00:29:11.090
for being there. So here you have a, a national
scale train moving through a dense slum market

00:29:11.090 --> 00:29:13.989
in Bangkok, and these kinds of proximities
are drivers of innovation; they're drivers

00:29:13.989 --> 00:29:23.409
of economic activity; and one of the reasons
we all move to cities is [inaudible].

00:29:23.409 --> 00:29:31.000
I love showing this to city planners. It -

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:32.000
[laughter]

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:37.659
They're real estate guys; now where do you
begin?

00:29:37.659 --> 00:29:38.659
[laughter]

00:29:38.659 --> 00:29:46.210
The poor people of the world are the slums
and the squatter cities are the greatest people

00:29:46.210 --> 00:29:57.479
there are. They use the least energy and the
least materials, but they're that green because

00:29:57.479 --> 00:30:08.229
they're poor and they do not chose to remain
that poor.

00:30:08.229 --> 00:30:15.820
Now this particular guy told the photographer
[inaudible]: "For toilet purposes we have

00:30:15.820 --> 00:30:25.739
to go outside." This is in the Dharavi slum
in Mumbai. "It's a problem; we have to go

00:30:25.739 --> 00:30:46.510
in the road. The electricity is on for two
days and off two days or not on at all. We

00:30:46.510 --> 00:30:57.299
don't have much space for the children to
play in; they use the road to play in and

00:30:57.299 --> 00:31:05.009
accidents take place again and again. I'm
not studied at all and am illiterate. For

00:31:05.009 --> 00:31:13.130
work I stitch government jeans and pants.
It's fine but the workday ends late. I want

00:31:13.130 --> 00:31:22.340
to educate my kids; 'til the day I die I'll
educate them. As long as I'm around that's

00:31:22.340 --> 00:31:23.340
guaranteed."

00:31:23.340 --> 00:31:34.750
That's a world changing event. The kids getting
educated in cities, fewer of them typically

00:31:34.750 --> 00:31:47.450
in birth rate drops below two point one per
woman as soon as they get into town and that

00:31:47.450 --> 00:32:12.940
combination is changing worlds. So what we're
looking at over the next 30 years is a global

00:32:12.940 --> 00:32:24.429
South full of huge growing cities, new cities
full of young people and here in the North

00:32:24.429 --> 00:32:31.700
basically old cities increasingly full of
people who look like me; old people.

00:32:31.700 --> 00:32:42.200
And where do you think the action's gonna
be? Because all the cities in the world want

00:32:42.200 --> 00:33:00.909
to get to this state which is not usually
green, it's usually a beautiful golden yellow.

00:33:00.909 --> 00:33:18.289
Cities require base load power and to get
to the power issue right now we get base load

00:33:18.289 --> 00:33:28.990
electricity from just three sources. Mostly
coal and gas, some hydro, some nuclear. In

00:33:28.990 --> 00:33:45.779
terms of constant base load there is, so far
no other source. We hope it gets mass storage

00:33:45.779 --> 00:33:50.860
for solar to wind, but they don't, they're
not on line yet.

00:33:50.860 --> 00:33:55.740
From the green standpoint the main argument
for nuclear is when you compare what happens

00:33:55.740 --> 00:34:02.169
with base, the waste products. That beautiful
monogrammed cook pan would contain -

00:34:02.169 --> 00:34:03.169
[laughter]

00:34:03.169 --> 00:34:14.130
a lifetime's worth of spent fuel from nuclear
electricity. Whereas just one day in a normal

00:34:14.130 --> 00:34:27.080
one gigawatt coal fired plant you see 19,000
tons of carbon dioxide coming out along with

00:34:27.080 --> 00:34:35.181
no end of slurry and flash and the rest of
it.

00:34:35.181 --> 00:34:51.350
Where does the waste go? Nuclear waste and
20 tons of fuel becomes 20 tons of waste goes

00:34:51.350 --> 00:35:04.620
into two dry cask storage back in the parking
lot. Two point nine million tons of coal turns

00:35:04.620 --> 00:35:13.680
into eight million tons of carbon dioxide
which goes into everybody's atmosphere where

00:35:13.680 --> 00:35:17.171
we can't do anything about it.

00:35:17.171 --> 00:35:24.040
So when you compare the lifetime greenhouse
gas emissions of nuclear it's down there with

00:35:24.040 --> 00:35:29.590
hydro and wind and, and still ahead of solar.

00:35:29.590 --> 00:35:39.850
Just a thing or two to say about wind. It's
pretty major infrastructure by now. And it

00:35:39.850 --> 00:35:50.390
takes not just an ecological footprint on
the land but a physical footprint on the industrialized

00:35:50.390 --> 00:35:56.790
landscape to the point of one gigawatt which
isn't constant taking up about 250 square

00:35:56.790 --> 00:35:57.790
miles of industrialized land.

00:35:57.790 --> 00:36:04.910
Solar is even tougher. Here in California
take a pretty place out in the desert and

00:36:04.910 --> 00:36:09.630
bulldoze it for solar farms and one gigawatt
takes 50 square miles. And just in case you

00:36:09.630 --> 00:36:11.930
think that's a particularly pretty or spectacular
place in the desert there's of course a Google

00:36:11.930 --> 00:36:18.840
indicator of where the photograph was taken.
It's an ordinary spot that is exactly the

00:36:18.840 --> 00:36:24.820
kind of places that are being dozed for solar
farms.

00:36:24.820 --> 00:36:38.680
Not that I'm against solar or wind. But it's,
as environmentalists starting to learn the

00:36:38.680 --> 00:36:46.270
trade off,
Saul Griffith has gone through the numbers

00:36:46.270 --> 00:36:56.700
and figured out that to really stabilize the
climate we need 13 terawatts of new clean

00:36:56.700 --> 00:37:13.100
