00:49:56.990 --> 00:49:57.990
One other quick subject: good old genetically
modified organisms; genetically engineered

00:49:57.990 --> 00:50:07.130
food crops. For some reason my fellow environmentalists
became deeply adverse to it; frankenfood.

00:50:07.130 --> 00:50:28.740
And it was based on I think ignorance that,
the notion that if you take genes from one

00:50:28.740 --> 00:50:32.240
species and put 'em in another species there's
something profoundly unnatural about that.

00:50:32.240 --> 00:50:43.750
It's not unnatural for microorganisms, they've
been doing it for 3.5 billion years. It's

00:50:43.750 --> 00:50:50.360
how a great deal of evolution has occurred;
my translation of genes from one organism

00:50:50.360 --> 00:50:54.480
to the next. We're just finally picking up
on that technology called a form of biomimicry.

00:50:54.480 --> 00:50:58.630
One of the things to ask with-- I love that
poisonous green color.

00:50:58.630 --> 00:50:59.630
[laughter]

00:50:59.630 --> 00:51:00.640
Yeah.

00:51:00.640 --> 00:51:06.883
Okay, who's actually using this? Well the
Amish for one.

00:51:06.883 --> 00:51:07.883
[laughter]

00:51:07.883 --> 00:51:08.883
Were usually very suspicious of any new technology
but they are also some of the best farmers

00:51:08.883 --> 00:51:09.883
in America. They know good seeds when they
see it. They were one of the early adopters

00:51:09.883 --> 00:51:10.883
of Bt corn for example.

00:51:10.883 --> 00:51:11.883
Likewise all around the world it's been picked
up by many developing countries such as South

00:51:11.883 --> 00:51:13.300
Africa where engineered white maize is one
of the most popular food crops there.

00:51:13.300 --> 00:51:15.240
There's three books I'll quickly recommend
here: Gordon Conway's The Doubly Green Revolution;

00:51:15.240 --> 00:51:16.910
two local folks Tomorrow's Table; Pamela Ronald
is a genetic engineer at UC Davis married

00:51:16.910 --> 00:51:17.910
to an organic farming teacher named Raoul
Adamchak. They think the combination of organic

00:51:17.910 --> 00:51:18.910
and engineered is the ideal way to go with
agriculture. I'd have to agree.

00:51:18.910 --> 00:51:19.910
A good survey of the area is Nina Fedoroff's
Mendel In The Kitchen.

00:51:19.910 --> 00:51:20.910
This is the most successful agricultural revolution
in history basically. It has taken off so

00:51:20.910 --> 00:51:21.910
rapidly and my fellow environmentalists keep
saying that it's somehow bad for farmers,

00:51:21.910 --> 00:51:22.910
but the farmers haven't gotten that message.

00:51:22.910 --> 00:51:23.910
[laughter]

00:51:23.910 --> 00:51:24.910
They think these are better seeds; they like
plants that they can get ahead of the weeds

00:51:24.910 --> 00:51:25.910
with, that they can get ahead of the pests
with, and that doesn't do a lot of damage

00:51:25.910 --> 00:51:26.910
to the landscape.

00:51:26.910 --> 00:51:27.910
So in the case of soy beans, for example,
most of the world's soy beans now are, are

00:51:27.910 --> 00:51:28.910
herbicide tolerant; that means that you don't
have to plow the ground to keep the weeds

00:51:28.910 --> 00:51:29.910
down. No till agriculture is absolutely one
of the best things you can do ecologically

00:51:29.910 --> 00:51:30.910
and it's a direct result of genetic engineering.

00:51:30.910 --> 00:51:31.910
As for the moral and ethical issues, The Nuffield
Council on Bioethics in England explored this

00:51:31.910 --> 00:51:32.910
subject twice in great depth, and came up
with the conclusion that there is a moral

00:51:32.910 --> 00:51:33.910
imperative for making GM crops readily and
economically available to anybody in the developing

00:51:33.910 --> 00:51:34.910
world that wants it.

00:51:34.910 --> 00:51:35.910
Now this is not just for the developing world.
Yeah, there are a number of things that are

00:51:35.910 --> 00:51:36.910
being done for especially tropical plants
that have not been bred up to their full capabilities,

00:51:36.910 --> 00:51:37.910
and so you have some fairly lousy food like
Cassava which is good for storage but not

00:51:37.910 --> 00:51:38.910
much else that 800 million people live on.
Or sorghum that 500 million people live on.

00:51:38.910 --> 00:51:39.910
Bill and Melinda Gates' Foundation put money
into BioCassava Plus. It is improved eight

00:51:39.910 --> 00:51:40.910
ways including producing the damn cyanide
that is natural in the plant.

00:51:40.910 --> 00:51:41.910
Down on the lower end of the scale you see
things that are gonna be of great interest

00:51:41.910 --> 00:51:42.910
to us such as not only an allergy-free peanut
but a pig with omega-3 fatty acids in it.

00:51:42.910 --> 00:51:43.910
So it's as healthy for you, your system and
your heart as eating wild fish and it would

00:51:43.910 --> 00:51:44.910
be fine with me if you didn't eat a wild fish
and ate a pig instead. Or even better there's

00:51:44.910 --> 00:51:45.910
a soy bean that has this capability coming
along from everybody's favorite enemy Monsanto.

00:51:45.910 --> 00:51:46.910
They're finally doing some crops that are
gonna be nutritious.

00:51:46.910 --> 00:51:47.910
And increasingly there will be medical benefits
as well in some of these engineered foods.

00:51:47.910 --> 00:51:48.910
The engineering standpoint on this is the
Rob Carlson, the Carlson curve, is pointing

00:51:48.910 --> 00:51:49.910
out that even though recombinant DNA technology,
standard genetic engineering has been increasing

00:51:49.910 --> 00:51:50.910
its capabilities at a faster than a morris
Law rate.

00:51:50.910 --> 00:51:51.910
The new capabilities of synthetic biology,
that is of basically generating new genomes

00:51:51.910 --> 00:51:52.910
somewhat from scratch; that's moving even
faster than that.

00:51:52.910 --> 00:51:53.910
In order words, this is a technology which
is going to increasingly dominate everything

00:51:53.910 --> 00:51:54.910
including all the environmental issues we're
interested in.

