[laughter]

00:52:12.910 --> 00:52:13.910
One of the pleasures of working on this book
is I got to revisit ecology 50 years after

00:52:13.910 --> 00:52:14.910
studying it; a lot has changed. One of the
things that's come along is this term called

00:52:14.910 --> 00:52:15.910
ecosystem engineering. It's the sort of thing
that earthworms do beneficially; basically

00:52:15.910 --> 00:52:16.910
in the process of making the soil better for
earthworms it makes the soil better for everybody,

00:52:16.910 --> 00:52:17.910
including farmers.

00:52:17.910 --> 00:52:18.910
Likewise beavers famously make ponds which
then make habitat, ecotones and all the rest

00:52:18.910 --> 00:52:19.910
of it and multiply the diversity in any area
that they're permitted to do that.

00:52:19.910 --> 00:52:20.910
This is one of the reasons that bringing the
wolves back to Yellowstone was so great because

00:52:20.910 --> 00:52:21.910
the wolves ate the, scared enough of the elk
that the elk got out of the [inaudible] areas,

00:52:21.910 --> 00:52:22.910
stopped eating all the trees; the beavers
came back [inaudible] trees, started damming

00:52:22.910 --> 00:52:23.910
creeks and the biodiversity of those parts
of Yellowstone jumped immediately.

00:52:23.910 --> 00:52:24.910
One of the great inspirers for me and other
greens is Aldo Leopold. He basically inspired

00:52:24.910 --> 00:52:25.910
people to become ecosystem engineers by restoring
natural systems and then he showed how quickly

00:52:25.910 --> 00:52:26.910
he's done it with his own shack in Wisconsin
in Sand County where he took a really frapped

00:52:26.910 --> 00:52:27.910
out farm, planted a bunch of trees and lo
a few years later the forest was back.

00:52:27.910 --> 00:52:28.910
He undid damage on 150 acres.

00:52:28.910 --> 00:52:29.910
We're looking at having to undo damage on
a planet scale. And that's gonna get hairy

00:52:29.910 --> 00:52:30.910
'cause here's why.

00:52:30.910 --> 00:52:31.910
We're realizing that we may not get through
the easy ways to head off greenhouse gases

00:52:31.910 --> 00:52:32.910
and climate change. Mitigation may not succeed
soon enough. We see things like what happened

00:52:32.910 --> 00:52:33.910
in Copenhagen and that's pretty impressive.
We keep getting more bad news than good news

00:52:33.910 --> 00:52:34.910
from climate science. One still hopes that
there's gonna to be something that shows there's

00:52:34.910 --> 00:52:35.910
unique stable capability there but that has
yet to emerge.

00:52:35.910 --> 00:52:36.910
And then as people start looking at geoengineering
the realization is that it is shockingly cheap.

00:52:36.910 --> 00:52:37.910
For example, sometimes it's free.

00:52:37.910 --> 00:52:38.910
[laughter]

